    {
      "content": "Prerequisites for Premium Storage",
      "pos": [
        2391,
        2424
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are several prerequisites for using Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        2426,
        2484
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Machine Size",
      "pos": [
        2490,
        2502
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For using Premium Storage you will need to use DS series Virtual Machines (VM).",
      "pos": [
        2504,
        2583
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have not used DS Series machines in your cloud service before, you must delete the existing VM, keep the attached disks, and then create a new cloud service before recreating  the VM as DS* role size.",
      "pos": [
        2584,
        2791
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information on Virtual Machine sizes, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Machine and Cloud Service Sizes for Azure<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-size-specs.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2792,
        2927
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cloud Services",
      "pos": [
        2933,
        2947
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can only use DS* VMs with Premium Storage when they are created in a new cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        2949,
        3040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using SQL Server AlwaysOn in Azure, the AlwaysOn Listener will refer to the Azure Internal or External Load Balancer IP address that is associated with a cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        3041,
        3220
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article focuses on how to migrate while maintaining availability in this scenario.",
      "pos": [
        3221,
        3308
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3312,
        3401
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> A DS* Series must be the first VM that is deployed to the new Cloud Service."
    },
    {
      "content": "Regional VNETS",
      "pos": [
        3407,
        3421
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For  DS* VMs you must configure the Virtual Network (VNET) hosting your VMs to be regional.",
      "pos": [
        3423,
        3514
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This “widens” the VNET is to allow the larger VMs to be provisioned in other clusters and allow communication between them.",
      "pos": [
        3515,
        3638
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the following screenshot, the highlighted Location shows regional VNETs, whereas the first result shows a “narrow” VNET.",
      "pos": [
        3639,
        3762
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![RegionalVNET][1]",
      "pos": [
        3765,
        3783
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can raise a Microsoft support ticket to migrate to a regional VNET, Microsoft will make a change, then to complete the migration to regional VNETs, change the property AffinityGroup in the network configuration.",
      "pos": [
        3785,
        4000
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "First export the Network Configuration in PowerShell, and then replace the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>AffinityGroup<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property in the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>VirtualNetworkSite<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> element with a <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Location<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> property.",
      "pos": [
        4001,
        4170
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specify <ph id=\"ph1\">`Location = XXXX`</ph> where <ph id=\"ph2\">`XXXX`</ph> is an Azure region.",
      "pos": [
        4171,
        4229
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then import the new configuration.",
      "pos": [
        4230,
        4264
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, considering the following VNET configuration:",
      "pos": [
        4266,
        4324
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To move this to a regional VNET in West Europe, change the configuration to the following:",
      "pos": [
        4592,
        4682
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage Accounts",
      "pos": [
        4949,
        4965
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will need to create a new storage account that is configured for Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        4967,
        5052
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that the use of Premium Storage is set at the storage account, not on individual VHDs, however when using a DS* Series VM you can attach VHD’s from Premium and Standard Storage accounts.",
      "pos": [
        5053,
        5244
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You may consider this if you do not want to place the OS VHD on to the Premium Storage account.",
      "pos": [
        5245,
        5340
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        5342,
        5468
      ],
      "content": "The following <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>New-AzureStorageAccountPowerShell<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command with the \"Premium_LRS\" <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Type<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> creates a Premium Storage Account:"
    },
    {
      "content": "VHDs Cache Settings",
      "pos": [
        5637,
        5656
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The main difference between creating disks that are part of a Premium Storage account is the disk cache setting.",
      "pos": [
        5658,
        5770
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For SQL Server Data volume disks it is recommended that you use ‘<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Read Caching<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>’.",
      "pos": [
        5771,
        5854
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For Transaction log volumes, the disk cache setting should be set to ‘<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>None<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>’.",
      "pos": [
        5855,
        5935
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is different from the recommendations for Standard Storage accounts.",
      "pos": [
        5936,
        6009
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once the VHDs have been attached, the cache setting cannot be altered.",
      "pos": [
        6011,
        6081
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You would need to detach and reattach the VHD with an updated cahce setting.",
      "pos": [
        6082,
        6158
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Windows Storage Spaces",
      "pos": [
        6164,
        6186
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows Storage Spaces<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/hh831739.aspx)</ept> as you did with previous Standard Storage, this will allow you to migrate a VM that is already utilizing Storage Spaces.",
      "pos": [
        6188,
        6398
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The example in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Appendix<ept id=\"p1\">](#appendix-migrating-a-multisite-alwayson-cluster-to-premium-storage)</ept> (step 9 and forward) demonstrates the Powershell code to extract and import a VM with multiple attached VHDs.",
      "pos": [
        6399,
        6603
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage Pools were used with Standard Azure storage account to enhance throughput and reduce latency.",
      "pos": [
        6606,
        6707
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might find value in testing Storage Pools with Premium Storage for new deployments, but they do add additional complexity with storage setup.",
      "pos": [
        6708,
        6853
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How to find which Azure Virtual Disks Map to Storage Pools",
      "pos": [
        6861,
        6919
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As there are different cache setting recommendations for attached VHDs, you might decide to copy the VHDs to a Premium Storage account.",
      "pos": [
        6921,
        7056
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, when you reattach them to the new DS series VM, you might need to alter the cache settings.",
      "pos": [
        7057,
        7157
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is simpler to apply the Premium Storage recommended cache settings when you have separate VHDs for the SQL Data files and log files (rather than a single VHD that contains both).",
      "pos": [
        7158,
        7339
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> If you have SQL Server data and log files on the same volume, the caching option you choose depends on the IO access patterns for your database workloads.",
      "pos": [
        7344,
        7511
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Only testing can demonstrate which caching option is best for this scenario.",
      "pos": [
        7512,
        7588
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However if you are using Windows Storage Spaces which are made up of multiple VHDs you will need to look at your original scripts to identify which attached VHDs are in what specific pool, so you can then set the cache settings accordingly for each disk.",
      "pos": [
        7590,
        7844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you do not have original script available to show you which VHDs map to the storage pool, you can use the following steps to determine the disk/storage pool mapping.",
      "pos": [
        7846,
        8014
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For each disk, use the following steps:",
      "pos": [
        8016,
        8055
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8060,
        8126
      ],
      "content": "Get list of disks attached to VM with the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Get-AzureVM<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command:"
    },
    {
      "content": "Get-AzureVM -ServiceName",
      "pos": [
        8132,
        8156
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "-Name",
      "pos": [
        8171,
        8176
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "| Get-AzureDataDisk",
      "pos": [
        8186,
        8205
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note the Diskname and LUN.",
      "pos": [
        8210,
        8236
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![DisknameAndLUN][2]",
      "pos": [
        8242,
        8262
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Remote desktop into the VM.",
      "pos": [
        8267,
        8294
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then go to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Computer Management<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> | <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Device Manager<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> | <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Disk Drives<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8295,
        8369
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Look at the  properties of each of the ‘Microsoft Virtual Disks’",
      "pos": [
        8370,
        8434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![VirtualDiskProperties][3]",
      "pos": [
        8440,
        8467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The LUN number here is a reference to the LUN number you specify when attaching the VHD to the VM.",
      "pos": [
        8472,
        8570
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For the ‘Microsoft Virtual Disk’ go to the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Details<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab, then in the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Property<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> list, go to <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Driver Key<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8574,
        8686
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Value<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, note the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Offset<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, which is 0002 in the following screenshot.",
      "pos": [
        8687,
        8768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The 0002 denotes the PhysicalDisk2 that the storage pool references.",
      "pos": [
        8769,
        8837
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![VirtualDiskPropertyDetails][4]",
      "pos": [
        8843,
        8875
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For each storage pool dump out the associated disks:",
      "pos": [
        8880,
        8932
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Get-StoragePool -FriendlyName AMS1pooldata | Get-PhysicalDisk",
      "pos": [
        8938,
        8999
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![GetStoragePool][5]",
      "pos": [
        9005,
        9025
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Now you can use this information to associate attached VHDs to Physical Disks in Storage Pools.",
      "pos": [
        9028,
        9123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once you have mapped VHDs to Physical Disks in Storage Pools you can then detach and copy them over to a Premium Storage account, then attach them with the correct cache setting.",
      "pos": [
        9125,
        9303
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Please see the example in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Appendix<ept id=\"p1\">](#appendix-migrating-a-multisite-alwayson-cluster-to-premium-storage)</ept>, steps 8 through 12.",
      "pos": [
        9304,
        9434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These steps show how to extract a VM-attached VHD disk configuration to a CSV file, copy the VHDs, alter the disk configuration cache settings, and finally redeploy the VM as a DS series VM with all the attached disks.",
      "pos": [
        9435,
        9653
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VM Storage Bandwidth and VHD Storage Throughput",
      "pos": [
        9659,
        9706
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The amount of storage performance depends on the DS* VM size specified and the VHD sizes.",
      "pos": [
        9709,
        9798
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VMs have different allowances for the number of VHDs that can be attached and the maximum bandwidth they will support (MB/s).",
      "pos": [
        9799,
        9928
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For the specific bandwidth numbers, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Machine and Cloud Service Sizes for Azure<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-size-specs.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9929,
        10053
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Increased IOPS are achieved with larger disk sizes.",
      "pos": [
        10055,
        10106
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should consider this when you think about your migration path.",
      "pos": [
        10107,
        10173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>see the table for IOPS and Disk Types<ept id=\"p1\">](../storage-premium-storage-preview-portal.md#scalability-and-performance-targets-when-using-premium-storage)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        10174,
        10336
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Finally, consider that VMs have different maximum disk bandwidths they will support for all disks attached.",
      "pos": [
        10339,
        10446
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Under high load, you could saturate the maximum disk bandwidth available for that VM role size.",
      "pos": [
        10447,
        10542
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example a Standard_DS14 will support up to 512MB/s; therefore, with three P30 disks you could saturate the disk bandwidth of the VM.",
      "pos": [
        10543,
        10679
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But in this example, the throughput limit could be exceeded depending on the mix of read and write IOs.",
      "pos": [
        10680,
        10783
      ]
    },
    {
