        18289,
        18325
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Step 6: Add Image disk to Azure disk Repository in Subscription",
      "pos": [
        18375,
        18438
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> You may find that even though the status reports as success, you could still get a disk lease error.",
      "pos": [
        18646,
        18759
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, wait about 10 minutes.",
      "pos": [
        18760,
        18796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Step 7:  Build the VM",
      "pos": [
        18803,
        18824
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here you are building the VM from your image and attaching two Premium Storage VHDs:",
      "pos": [
        18825,
        18909
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Existing Deployments that do not use AlwaysOn Availability Groups",
      "pos": [
        20326,
        20391
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        20395,
        20522
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> For existing deployments, first see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Prerequisites<ept id=\"p1\">](#prerequisites-for-premium-storage)</ept> section of this topic."
    },
    {
      "content": "There are different considerations for SQL Server deployments that do not use AlwaysOn Availbility Groups and those that do.",
      "pos": [
        20524,
        20648
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are not using AlwaysOn and have an existing standalone SQL Server, you can upgrade to Premium Storage by using a new cloud service and storage account.",
      "pos": [
        20649,
        20807
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider the following options:",
      "pos": [
        20808,
        20839
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Create a new SQL Server VM<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        20843,
        20874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can create a new SQL Server VM that uses a Premium Storage account, as documented in New Deployments.",
      "pos": [
        20875,
        20980
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then backup and restore your SQL Server configuration and user databases.",
      "pos": [
        20981,
        21054
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application will need to be updated to reference the new SQL Server if it is being accessed internally or externally.",
      "pos": [
        21055,
        21176
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You would need to copy all ‘out of db’ objects as if you were doing a Side by Side (SxS) SQL Server migration.",
      "pos": [
        21177,
        21287
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This includes objects such as logins, certificates, and linked servers.",
      "pos": [
        21288,
        21359
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Migrate an existing SQL Server VM<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        21362,
        21400
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This will require taking the SQL Server VM offline, then transferring it to a new cloud service, which includes copying all of its attached VHDs to the Premium Storage account.",
      "pos": [
        21401,
        21577
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the VM comes online, the application will reference the server host name as before.",
      "pos": [
        21578,
        21666
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Be aware that the size of the existing disk will affect the performance characteristics.",
      "pos": [
        21667,
        21755
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, a 400 GB disk gets rounded up to a P20.",
      "pos": [
        21756,
        21808
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you know that you do not require that disk performance, then you could recreate the VM as a DS Series VM, and attach Premium Storage VHDs of the size/performance specification you require.",
      "pos": [
        21809,
        22000
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then you could detach and reattach the SQL DB files.",
      "pos": [
        22001,
        22053
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> When copying the VHD disks you should beaware of the size, depending on the size will mean what Premium Storage Disk type they fall into, this determines disk performance specification.",
      "pos": [
        22057,
        22255
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure will round up to the nearest disk size, so if you have a 400GB disk, this will be rounded up to a P20.",
      "pos": [
        22256,
        22364
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Depending on your existing IO requirements of the OS VHD, you might not need to migrate this to a Premium Storage account.",
      "pos": [
        22365,
        22487
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your SQL Server is accessed externally, then the cloud service VIP will change.",
      "pos": [
        22489,
        22571
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will also have to update endptoints, ACLs, and DNS settings.",
      "pos": [
        22572,
        22636
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Existing Deployments that use AlwaysOn Availability Groups",
      "pos": [
        22641,
        22699
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        22703,
        22830
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> For existing deployments, first see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Prerequisites<ept id=\"p1\">](#prerequisites-for-premium-storage)</ept> section of this topic."
    },
    {
      "content": "Intially in this section we will look at how AlwaysOn interacts with Azure Networking.",
      "pos": [
        22832,
        22918
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We will then break down migrations in to two scenarios: migrations where some downtime can be tolerated and migrations where you must achieve minimal downtime.",
      "pos": [
        22919,
        23078
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On-premises SQL Server AlwaysOn Availability Groups use a Listener on-premises that registers a virtual DNS name along with an IP address that is shared between one or more SQL Servers.",
      "pos": [
        23080,
        23265
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When clients connect they are routed through the listener IP to the Primary SQL Server.",
      "pos": [
        23266,
        23353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is the server that owns the AlwaysOn IP resource at that time.",
      "pos": [
        23354,
        23421
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![DeploymentsUseAlwaysOn][6]",
      "pos": [
        23424,
        23452
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Microsoft Azure you can have only one IP address assigned to a NIC on the VM, so in order to achieve the same layer of abstraction as on-premises, Azure utilizes the IP address that is assigned to the Internal/External Load Balancers (ILB/ELB).",
      "pos": [
        23454,
        23701
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The IP resource that is shared between the servers is set to the same IP as the ILB/ELB.",
      "pos": [
        23702,
        23790
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is published in the DNS, and client traffic is passed through the ILB/ELB to the Primary SQL Server replica.",
      "pos": [
        23791,
        23904
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The ILB/ELB knows which SQL Server is primary since it uses probes to probe the AlwaysOn IP resource.",
      "pos": [
        23905,
        24006
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the previous example, it probes each node that has an endpoint referenced by the ELB/ILB, whichever responds is the Primary SQL Server.",
      "pos": [
        24007,
        24145
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        24150,
        24333
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The ILB and ELB are both assigned to a particular Azure cloud service, therefore any cloud migration in Azure will most likely mean that the Load Balancer IP will change."
    },
    {
      "content": "Migrating AlwaysOn deployments that can allow some downtime",
      "pos": [
        24340,
        24399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two strategies to migrate AlwaysOn deployments that allow for some downtime:",
      "pos": [
        24401,
        24487
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Add more secondary replicas to an existing AlwaysOn Cluster",
      "pos": [
        24494,
        24553
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Migrate to a new AlwaysOn Cluster",
      "pos": [
        24561,
        24594
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "1. Add more Secondary Replicas to an Existing AlwaysOn Cluster",
      "pos": [
        24603,
        24665
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One strategy is to add more secondaries to the AlwaysOn Availability Group.",
      "pos": [
        24667,
        24742
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to add these into a new cloud service and update the listener with the new load balancer IP.",
      "pos": [
        24743,
        24844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Points of Downtime:",
      "pos": [
        24853,
        24872
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cluster Validation.",
      "pos": [
        24876,
        24895
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Testing AlwaysOn failovers for New Secondaries.",
      "pos": [
        24898,
        24945
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using Windows Storage Pools within the VM for higher IO throughput, then these will be taken offline during a Full Cluster Validation.",
      "pos": [
        24947,
        25092
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The validation test is required when you add nodes to the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        25093,
        25159
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The time it takes to run the test can vary, so you should test this in your representative test environment to get an approximate time of how long this will take.",
      "pos": [
        25160,
        25322
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should provision time where you can perform manual failover and chaos testing on the newly added nodes to ensure AlwaysOn High Availability functions as expected.",
      "pos": [
        25325,
        25491
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![DeploymentUseAlwaysOn2][7]",
      "pos": [
        25493,
        25521
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        25525,
        25641
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> You should stop all instances of SQL Server where the Storage Pools are used before the Validaion runs."
    },
    {
      "content": "High Level Steps",
      "pos": [
        25649,
        25665
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create two new SQL Servers in new cloud service with attached Premium Storage.",
      "pos": [
        25670,
        25748
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        25752,
        25807
      ],
      "content": "Copy over FULL backups and restore with <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>NORECOVERY<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Copy over ‘out of user DB’ dependent objects, such as logins etc.",
      "pos": [
        25811,
        25876
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create new a new Internal Load Balancer (ILB) or use an External Load Balancer (ELB), and then set up Load Balanced Endpoints on both new nodes.",
      "pos": [
        25880,
        26024
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        26027,
        26115
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Check all Nodes have the correct Endpoint configuration before you continue"
    },
    {
      "content": "Stop User/Application Access to the SQL Server (if using Storage Pools).",
      "pos": [
        26120,
        26192
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Stop SQL Server Engine Services on All Nodes (if using Storage Pools).",
      "pos": [
        26196,
        26266
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Add new Nodes to cluster and run full validation.",
      "pos": [
        26270,
        26319
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once Validation is successful, start all SQL Server Services.",
      "pos": [
        26324,
        26385
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backup Transaction logs, and restore user databases.",
      "pos": [
        26389,
        26441
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        26445,
        26538
      ],
      "content": "Add new nodes into the AlwaysOn Availability Group and place replication into <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Syncronous<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Add the IP address resource of the new Cloud Service ILB/ELB through PowerShell for AlwaysOn based on the Multi-site example in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Appendix<ept id=\"p1\">](#appendix-migrating-a-multisite-alwayson-cluster-to-premium-storage)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        26543,
        26755
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Windows clustering, set the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Possible owners<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> of the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>IP Address<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> resource to the new nodes old.",
      "pos": [
        26756,
        26859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See the ‘Adding IP Address Resource on Same Subnet’ section of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Appendix<ept id=\"p1\">](#appendix-migrating-a-multisite-alwayson-cluster-to-premium-storage)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        26860,
        27007
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Failover to one of the new nodes.",
      "pos": [
        27011,
        27044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make the new nodes Auto Failover Partners and test failovers.",
      "pos": [
        27048,
        27109
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Remove original nodes from Availability Group.",
      "pos": [
        27113,
        27159
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Advantages",
      "pos": [
        27167,
        27177
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "New SQL Servers can be tested (SQL Server and Application) before they are added to AlwaysOn.",
      "pos": [
        27181,
        27274
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can change the VM size and customize the storage to your exact requirements.",
      "pos": [
        27277,
        27357
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, it would be beneficial to keep all the SQL file paths the same.",
      "pos": [
        27358,
        27430
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can control when the transfer of the DB backups to the Secondary Replicas are started.",
      "pos": [
        27433,
        27523
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This differs from using Azure <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Start-AzureStorageBlobCopy<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> commandlet to copy VHDs, because that is an asynchronous copy.",
      "pos": [
        27524,
        27647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Disadvantages",
      "pos": [
        27655,
        27668
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When using Windows Storage Pools, there is Cluster downtime during the Full Cluster Validation for the new additional nodes.",
      "pos": [
        27671,
        27795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Depending on the SQL Server Version and the existing number of secondary replicas, you might not be able to add more secondary replicas without removing existing secondaries.",
      "pos": [
        27799,
        27973
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There could be long SQL data transfer time while setting up the secondaries.",
      "pos": [
        27976,
        28052
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is additional cost during migration while you have new machines running in paralell.",
      "pos": [
        28055,
        28145
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "2. Migrate to a New AlwaysOn Cluster",
      "pos": [
        28152,
        28188
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another strategy is to create a brand new AlwaysOn Cluster with brand new nodes in new cloud service and then redirect the clients to use it.",
      "pos": [
        28190,
        28331
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Points of Downtime",
      "pos": [
        28339,
        28357
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is downtime when you transfer applications and users to the new AlwaysOn listener.",
      "pos": [
        28359,
        28447
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The downtime depends on:",
      "pos": [
        28448,
        28472
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The time taken to restore final transaction log backups to databases on new servers.",
      "pos": [
        28476,
        28560
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The time taken to update client applications to use new AlwaysOn listener.",
      "pos": [
        28563,
        28637
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Advantages",
      "pos": [
        28645,
        28655
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can test the actual production environment, SQL Server, and OS build changes.",
      "pos": [
        28659,
        28740
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You have the option to customize the storage and to potentially reduce size of VM.",
      "pos": [
        28743,
        28825
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This could result in cost reduction.",
      "pos": [
        28826,
        28862
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can update your SQL Server build or version during this process.",
      "pos": [
        28865,
        28933
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also upgrade the Operating System.",
      "pos": [
        28934,
        28976
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The previous AlwaysOn Cluster can act as a solid rollback target.",
      "pos": [
        28979,
        29044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Disadvantages",
      "pos": [
        29052,
        29065
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to change the DNS name of the listener if you want both AlwaysOn clusters running simultaneously.",
      "pos": [
        29069,
        29175
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This adds administration overhead during the migration as client application strings must reflect the new Listener name.",
      "pos": [
        29176,
        29296
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must implement a synchronization mechanism between the two environments to keep them as close as possible to minimize the final synchronization requirements before migration.",
      "pos": [
        29299,
        29477
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is added cost during migration while you have the new environment running.",
      "pos": [
        29480,
        29560
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Migrating AlwaysOn Deployments for Minimal Downtime",
      "pos": [
        29566,
        29617
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two strategies for migrating AlwaysOn deployments for minimal downtime:",
      "pos": [
        29619,
        29700
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Utilize an Existing Secondary: Single-Site",
      "pos": [
        29707,
        29749
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Utilize Existing Secondary Replica(s): Multi-Site",
      "pos": [
        29757,
        29806
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "1. Utilize an Existing Secondary: Single-Site",
      "pos": [
        29815,
        29860
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One strategy for minimal downtime is to take an existing cloud secondary and remove it from the current cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        29862,
        29980
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then copy the VHDs to the new Premium Storage account, and create the VM in the new cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        29981,
        30079
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then update the listener in clustering and failover.",
      "pos": [
        30080,
        30132
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Points of Downtime",
      "pos": [
        30140,
        30158
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is downtime when you update the final node with the Load Balanaced endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        30162,
        30244
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your client reconnection might be delayed depending on your client/DNS configuration.",
      "pos": [
        30247,
        30332
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is additional downtime if you choose to take the AlwaysOn Cluster group offline to swap out the IP addresses.",
      "pos": [
        30335,
        30450
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can avoid this by using an OR dependancy and Possible Owners for the added IP Address resource.",
      "pos": [
        30451,
        30550
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See the ‘Adding IP Address Resource on Same Subnet’ section of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Appendix<ept id=\"p1\">](#appendix-migrating-a-multisite-alwayson-cluster-to-premium-storage)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        30551,
        30698
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> When you want the added node to partake in as an AlwaysOn Failover Partner, you need to add an Azure Endpoint with a reference to the Load Balanced Set.",
      "pos": [
        30702,
        30867
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you run the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Add-AzureEndpoint<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> command to do this, current connections to remain open, but new connections to the listener will not be able to be established until the load balancer has updated.",
      "pos": [
        30868,
        31070
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In testing this was seen to last 90-120seconds, this should be tested.",
      "pos": [
        31071,
        31141
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Advantages",
      "pos": [
        31150,
        31160
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "No extra cost incurred during migration.",
      "pos": [
        31164,
        31204
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A one-to-one migration.",
      "pos": [
        31207,
        31230
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Reduced complexity.",
      "pos": [
        31233,
        31252
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Allows for increased IOPS from Premium Storage SKUs.",
      "pos": [
        31255,
        31307
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the disks are detached from the VM and copied to the new cloud service, a 3rd party tool can be used to increase the VHD size, which provides higher throughputs.",
      "pos": [
        31308,
        31474
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For increasing VHD sizes, see this <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>forum discussion<ept id=\"p1\">](https://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/azure/4a9bcc9e-e5bf-4125-9994-7c154c9b0d52/resizing-azure-data-disk?forum=WAVirtualMachinesforWindows)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        31475,
        31673
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Disadvantages",
      "pos": [
        31681,
        31694
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is a temporary loss of HA and DR during migration.",
      "pos": [
        31698,
        31754
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As this is a 1:1 migration, you will have to use a minimum VM size that will support your number of VHDs, so you might not be able to downsize your VMs.",
      "pos": [
        31757,
        31909
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This scenario would use the Azure <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Start-AzureStorageBlobCopy<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> commandlet, which is asynchronous.",
      "pos": [
        31912,
        32011
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is no SLA on copy completion.",
      "pos": [
        32012,
        32047
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The time of the copies varies, while this depends on wait in queue it will also depend on the amount of data to transfer.",
      "pos": [
        32048,
        32169
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The copy time increases if the transfer is going to another Azure data center that supports Premium Storage in another region.",
      "pos": [
        32170,
        32296
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you just have 2 nodes, consider a possible mitigation in case the copy takes longer than in testing.",
