    {
      "content": "Step 2: Increase the Permitted Failures on Resources",
      "pos": [
        39456,
        39508
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On certain resources that belong to your AlwaysOn Availability Group there are limits on how many failures that can occur in a period, where the cluster service will attempt to restart the resource group.",
      "pos": [
        39520,
        39724
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is recommended you increase this whilst you are walking through this procedure, since if you don’t manually failover and trigger failovers by shutting down machines you can get close to this limit.",
      "pos": [
        39725,
        39925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It would be prudent to double the failure allowance, to do this in Failover Cluster Manager, go to the Properties of the AlwaysOn resource group:",
      "pos": [
        39927,
        40072
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![Appendix3][13]",
      "pos": [
        40075,
        40091
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Change the Maximum Failures to 6.",
      "pos": [
        40093,
        40126
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Step 3: Addition IP Address Resource for Cluster Group",
      "pos": [
        40133,
        40187
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have only one IP address for the Cluster Group and this is aligned to the cloud subnet, beware, if you accidentally take offline all cluster nodes in the cloud on that network then the Cluster IP resource and Cluster Network Name will not be able to come online.",
      "pos": [
        40200,
        40469
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the event of this it will prevent updates to other cluster resources.",
      "pos": [
        40470,
        40542
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Step 4: DNS Configuration",
      "pos": [
        40550,
        40575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To implement a smooth transition depends on how DNS is being utilised and updated.",
      "pos": [
        40577,
        40659
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When AlwaysOn is installed, it creates a Windows Cluster Resource group, if you open Failover Cluster Manager, you will see that at a minimum it will have three resources, the two that the document refers to are:",
      "pos": [
        40660,
        40872
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Virtual Network Name (VNN) – This is the DNS name that client connect to when wanting to connect to SQL Servers via AlwaysOn.",
      "pos": [
        40876,
        41001
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "IP Address Resource – This is the IP address that associated with the VNN, you can have more than one, and in a multisite configuration you will have an IP address per site/subnet.",
      "pos": [
        41004,
        41184
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When connecting to SQL Sevrer, the SQL Server Client driver will retrieve the DNS records associated with the listener and try to connect to each AlwaysOn associated IP address, below we discuss some factors that can influence this.",
      "pos": [
        41186,
        41418
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The number of concurrent DNS records that are associated with the listener name depends not only on the number of IP addresses associated, but the ‘RegisterAllIpProviders’setting in Failover Clustering for the AlwaysON VNN resource.",
      "pos": [
        41420,
        41652
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you deploy AlwaysOn in Azure there are different steps to create the Listener and IP Addresses, you have to manually configure the ‘RegisterAllIpProviders’ to 1, this is different to an on premise AlwaysOn deployment where it is already set to 1.",
      "pos": [
        41654,
        41905
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If ‘RegisterAllIpProviders’ is 0, then you will only see one DNS record in DNS associated with the Listener:",
      "pos": [
        41908,
        42016
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![Appendix4][14]",
      "pos": [
        42018,
        42034
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If ‘RegisterAllIpProviders’ is 1:",
      "pos": [
        42036,
        42069
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "![Appendix5][15]",
      "pos": [
        42072,
        42088
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The code below will dump out the VNN settings and set it for you, please note, for the change to take effect you will need to take the the VNN offline and turn it back online, this taking the Listener offline causing client connectivity disruption.",
      "pos": [
        42090,
        42338
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a later migration step you will need to update the AlwaysOn listener with an updated IP address that will reference a load balancer, this will involve an IP Address resource removal and addition.",
      "pos": [
        42627,
        42825
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the IP update, you need to ensure the new IP address has been updated in DNS Zone and that the clients are updating their local DNS cache.",
      "pos": [
        42826,
        42970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you clients reside in a different network segment and reference a different DNS server, you need to consider what happens about DNS Zone Transfer during the migration, as the application reconnect time will be constrained by at least the Zone Transfer Time of any new IP addresses for the listener.",
      "pos": [
        42973,
        43274
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are under time constraint here, you should discuss and test forcing an incremental zone transfer with your Windows teams, and also put the DNS host record to a lower Time To Live (TTL), so the clients update.",
      "pos": [
        43275,
        43490
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Incremental Zone Transfers<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc958973.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Start-DnsServerZoneTransfer<ept id=\"p2\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/jj649917.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        43491,
        43686
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default the TTL for DNS Record that is associated with the Listener in AlwaysOn in Azure is 1200 seconds.",
      "pos": [
        43688,
        43796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You may wish to reduce this if you are under time constraint during your migration to ensure the clients update their DNS with the updated IP address for the listener.",
      "pos": [
        43797,
        43964
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can see and modify the configuration by dumping out the configuration of the VNN:",
      "pos": [
        43965,
        44050
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Please note, the lower the ‘HostRecordTTL’, a higher amount of DNS traffic will occur.",
      "pos": [
        44328,
        44414
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Client Application Settings",
      "pos": [
        44422,
        44449
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your SQL client application supports the .Net 4.5 SQLClient, then you can use ‘MULTISUBNETFAILOVER=TRUE’ keyword, this is recommended to be applied as it allows for faster connection to SQL AlwaysOn Availability Group during failover.",
      "pos": [
        44451,
        44688
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It enumerates through all IP addresses associated with the AlwaysOn listener in parallel, and performs a more aggressive TCP connection retry speed during a failover.",
      "pos": [
        44689,
        44855
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information regarding the settings above, please see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>MultiSubnetFailover Keyword and Associated Features<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/hh213080.aspx#MultiSubnetFailover)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        44857,
        45043
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Also see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>SqlClient Support for High Availability, Disaster Recovery<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/hh205662(v=vs.110).aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        45044,
        45174
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Step 5: Cluster Quorum Settings",
      "pos": [
        45181,
        45212
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As you are going to be taking out at least one SQL Server down at a time, you should modify the cluster quorum setting, if using File Share Witnes (FSW) with 2 nodes, you should set the quorum to allow node majority and utilise dynamic voting, and this is to allow for a single node to remain standing.",
      "pos": [
        45214,
        45516
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        45558,
        45773
      ],
      "content": "For more information on managing and configuring the cluster quorum, please see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configure and Manage the Quorum in a Windows Server 2012 Failover Cluster<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj612870.aspx)</ept>."
    },
    {
